		Comment <a href="#c_1713713466">9</a> by James Allen
		posted on 3/2/2009 at 10:18 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>One way to make exercising fun that I've found is using the Nintendo Wii. I use Wii sports about twice a week at the moment. I do the boxing for 30 minutes then tennis for about 20-30 minutes.<br>You'd be surprised at how good the work out is as long as you put maximum intensity into each move.<br>It's incredible how aggressive I can get while doing the boxing - I truly hate some of those boxy wii characters..lol.</p><p>On the remaining 3 days I do what I consider the most brutal and effective workout's I've ever used (and I've been working out regularly for about 10 years). They are part of the Bas Rutten MMA (Mixed Martial Arts) workout which was designed by Bas for traning for combat. Bas Rutten is a well known MMA athelete. They are audio only which means they never get boring and I've been doing them for about 4 years or so (sometimes inregularly but I always come back to them).</p><p>They are essentially based on Thai boxing although there is also a boxing workout and an all around workout (totally brutal circuit training based routine). The ultimate in the series is the all round fighting wokout which combines thai boxing punch / kick combos with sprawls where you have to hit the ground on all fours and then spring back up to continue the combos.. <br>Tough is an understatement and it can take months to build up to being able to handle this one.</p><p>The great thing is that they are only 30 minutes in length based around 2 or 3 minute rounds with 1 minute rest.<br>Makes it easier to fit into a routine I find, and due to the mental intensity the 30 minutes is probably equivalent to 1 - 1.5 hours of other exercising.</p><p>I can thoroughly recommend this work out if your at an intermediate to advanced level fitness wise. The 2 minute boxing rounds is a great start and you feel the results very quickly.</p><p>I intend to buy some free weights and bench soon to add into the mix. I recently switched to working out in the morning before hitting my desk to work.. It's working out a lot better than I thought and means I am able to do 5 days without problem.. Alot of this is all about finding a routine that 'fits'..</p><p>Sorry for the length of this post.. :)</p></div>
